8. SOLID Principles in Java (OOP)
âœ… SOLID Principles (OOP Best Practices)
Letter	Principle	Meaning
S	Single Responsibility Principle	One class â†’ one reason to change
O	Open/Closed Principle	Open for extension, closed for modification
L	Liskov Substitution Principle	Subtypes should replace base types safely
I	Interface Segregation Principle	No forced methods; use smaller interfaces
D	Dependency Inversion Principle	Depend on abstractions, not concrete classes
ğŸ”¹ 1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
ğŸ“Œ A class should have only one reason to change.
âŒ Bad Example:
class User {
    void saveToDatabase() { /* Save logic */ }
    void sendEmail() { /* Email logic */ }
}
âœ… Good Example:
class User {
    private String name;
    // Only user data
}

class UserRepository {
    void save(User user) {
        // Save to DB
    }
}

class EmailService {
    void sendWelcomeEmail(User user) {
        // Send email
    }
}

ğŸ”¹ 2. Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
ğŸ“Œ Classes should be open for extension, but closed for modification.
âŒ Bad Example:
class Discount {
    double calculate(String type, double amount) {
        if (type.equals("FESTIVAL")) return amount * 0.9;
        if (type.equals("REGULAR")) return amount * 0.95;
        return amount;
    }
}
âœ… Good Example (use polymorphism):
interface Discount {
    double apply(double amount);
}

class FestivalDiscount implements Discount {
    public double apply(double amount) { return amount * 0.9; }
}

class RegularDiscount implements Discount {
    public double apply(double amount) { return amount * 0.95; }
}

ğŸ”¹ 3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
ğŸ“Œ Subclasses should be substitutable for their parent classes.
âŒ Bad Example:
class Bird {
    void fly() { }
}

class Ostrich extends Bird {
    void fly() { throw new UnsupportedOperationException(); }
}
âœ… Good Example:
interface Bird { }

interface FlyingBird extends Bird {
    void fly();
}

class Parrot implements FlyingBird {
    public void fly() { System.out.println("Flying"); }
}

class Ostrich implements Bird {
    // No fly method â€” safe!
}

ğŸ”¹ 4. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
ğŸ“Œ Donâ€™t force a class to implement methods it doesnâ€™t need.
âŒ Bad Example:
interface Worker {
    void work();
    void eat();
}

class Robot implements Worker {
    public void work() { }
    public void eat() { } // Not applicable!
}
âœ… Good Example:
interface Workable {
    void work();
}

interface Eatable {
    void eat();
}

class Human implements Workable, Eatable {
    public void work() { }
    public void eat() { }
}

class Robot implements Workable {
    public void work() { }
}

ğŸ”¹ 5. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
ğŸ“Œ High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules; both should depend on abstractions.
âŒ Bad Example:
class MySQLDatabase {
    void connect() { }
}

class UserService {
    MySQLDatabase db = new MySQLDatabase();
}
âœ… Good Example:
interface Database {
    void connect();
}

class MySQLDatabase implements Database {
    public void connect() { }
}

class UserService {
    private Database db;

    UserService(Database db) {
        this.db = db;
    }
}
9. Spring AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming)
AOPÂ separates cross-cutting concerns (like logging, security, etc.) from business logic.
Â·Â 
Aspect: A concern like logging.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Join Point: A point in execution, like method call.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Advice: Code executed at a join point.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Pointcut: Expression that selects join points.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Weaving: Linking aspects to target objects.
Â·Â 
Example:
@Aspect
@Component
public class LoggingAspect {
Â Â Â Â @Before("execution(* com.example.service.*.*(..))")
Â Â Â Â public void logBefore(JoinPoint joinPoint) {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â System.out.println("Before Method: " + joinPoint.getSignature());
Â Â Â Â }
}


